<TITLE> Govt will consider subsidy-hit fertiliser dealers: Matia </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 7 (bdnews24.com) Agriculture minister Matia Chowdhury on Thursday said the government will consider the case of fertiliser dealers hit by falling prices induced by subsidy. Matia told bdnews24.com that many had bought fertiliser at high prices but it was subsidised, the prices fell "We know who has how much fertiliser. We will not deprive anyone." "Fertiliser dealers have been informed that the government will consider their cases," she added. Earlier in the day, Kafiluddin Ahmed, president of Bangladesh Fertiliser Dealers Association, told bdnews24.com that fertiliser was falling into ruin. Urea or non-urea, whatever the type, dealers and importers now have stock worth 2000 crore." There was no possibility of a fertiliser crisis before next monsoon, that is Jan 2010. Dealers were now in trouble with the huge amount of unsold stock. Storage is another problem. He said focusing only on export will not work. "The importers need to be pulled out of high debts," he said at the 15th AGM of the Association. Industry minister Dilip Barua and Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FBCCI) president Annisul Huq were present. bdnews2
